  "short": {
    "headline": "India’s population: 1.45 billion and counting",
    "dek": "As of 2024, India is the world’s most populous country. UN projections suggest it will cross 1.5 billion by 2030.",
    "body": "India's population has grown from 435 million in 1960 to 1.45 billion in 2024, according to the World Bank. The UN’s medium-variant projection places the population at 1.525 billion in 2030, with high- and low-fertility variants ranging from 1.547 billion to 1.504 billion. For 2030, the median projection estimates 785 million males and 740 million females. These figures underscore India’s demographic weight, though projections are model-based and subject to uncertainty."
  },
  "article": {
    "title": "How many people live in India? A look at the numbers",
    "standfirst": "India’s population is the largest in the world. Using the latest data from the World Bank and UN projections, we examine the current count, historical growth, and future scenarios.",
    "bodyMarkdown": "India’s population is a subject of global interest, not only for its sheer size but also for the pace of its growth. The most recent available figure, from the World Bank for 2024, puts India’s population at **1,450,935,791**. This is the latest actual estimate. For context, in 1960 the population was **435,990,338** — meaning India has added more than a billion people in six decades.\n\nThe United Nations World Population Prospects provides a more granular look. For the year 2000, the UN’s median estimate gives a total of **1,057,922,733**, with **547,253,435** males and **510,669,298** females. By 2030, the UN projects the median total will reach **1,525,138,844.5**, with **784,994,167** males and **740,144,677.5** females.\n\nWhat does a median projection mean? It is the middle of a range of possible futures based on assumptions about fertility, mortality, and migration. The UN also publishes high-fertility and low-fertility variants. The high-fertility scenario for 2030 yields **1,546,709,881** people, while the low-fertility scenario yields **1,503,569,098.5**. These numbers illustrate the sensitivity of population projections to small changes in fertility. For instance, the constant-fertility variant (assuming 2024 fertility remains unchanged) gives **1,529,359,836**, and the instant-replacement-fertility scenario gives **1,542,362,509**.\n\nThe sex composition of the population is also captured. For 2030, the median projection implies a sex ratio of about 106 males per 100 females (784,994,167 males to 740,144,677.5 females). In 2000, the ratio was roughly 107 males per 100 females (547,253,435 to 510,669,298).\n\nThese figures come from two authoritative sources. The World Bank’s “Population, total” indicator (SP.POP.TOTL) provides historical annual estimates from 1960 through 2024. The UN’s “Total population by sex” indicator from the World Population Prospects offers model-based estimates and projections, typically released every two years. The projections are not predictions but plausible scenarios based on current trends and assumptions.\n\nWhat the data does not tell us directly is the age structure, urban-rural distribution, or density. A population count alone cannot reveal whether the population is young or old, or whether it is concentrated in cities or spread across villages. Those details require additional indicators such as age-specific population or urban population share.\n\nWhy does this matter? India’s population size affects everything from resource allocation to economic planning, environmental impact, and international influence. The fact that the population is projected to continue growing — even under the low-fertility scenario — means that for at least the next few years, India will remain the world’s most populous country (a position it took from China around 2023, though that comparison is not in this data set).\n\nSome caveats are in order. The UN projections are model-based and rely on assumptions that may not hold. Census data, when available, can differ from these estimates. The World Bank figure itself is based on national census and survey data, and revisions can occur over time. There are no state-level or district-level data here, so this answer is about India as a whole.\n\nIn summary, as of 2024, India’s population is about 1.45 billion. Historical records show dramatic growth from 435 million in 1960. UN projections indicate that by 2030, the population will likely be around 1.525 billion, with a range of plausible outcomes between 1.50 and 1.55 billion depending on fertility trends. These numbers are essential for understanding India’s place in the world today and in the near future."
  },
